{{Infobox football biography | name = Miguel Montes | image = | fullname = Miguel Ángel Montes Moreno | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1980|2|12}} | birth_place = [[Sensuntepeque]], [[El Salvador]] | height = {{height|m=1.81|precision=0}} | position = [[Goalkeeper]] | currentclub = None | clubnumber = 1 | youthyears1 = 1995–1997 |youthclubs1 = Baygón ADET | years1 = 1998–2000 |clubs1 = [[C.D. Santa Clara de El Salvador|Santa Clara]] |caps1 = |goals1 = | years2 = 2000–2001 |clubs2 = [[ADET]] |caps2 = |goals2 = | years3 = 2001–2005 |clubs3 = [[Alianza F.C.|Alianza]] |caps3 =76 |goals3 =0 | years4 = 2005–2006 |clubs4 = [[C.D. Luis Ángel Firpo|Firpo]] |caps4 =20 |goals4 =0 | years5 = 2006–2007 |clubs5 = [[C.D. Chalatenango|Chalatenango]] |caps5 =21 |goals5 =0 | years6 = 2007–2009 |clubs6 = [[Nejapa F.C.|Nejapa]] |caps6 =46 |goals6 =3 | years7 = 2009–2011 |clubs7 = [[C.D. Águila|Águila]] |caps7 =56 |goals7 =0 | years8 = 2011–2012 |clubs8 = [[A.D. Isidro Metapán|Isidro Metapán]] |caps8 =29 |goals8= 0 | years9 = 2012–2013 |clubs9 = [[Alianza F.C.|Alianza]] |caps9 =10 |goals9= 0 | nationalyears1 = 2004–2011 |nationalteam1 = [[El Salvador national football team|El Salvador]] |nationalcaps1 = 43 |nationalgoals1 = 0 | pcupdate = 21 April 2011 | ntupdate = 19 June 2011 }}
{{spanish name 2|Montes|Moreno}} '''Miguel Ángel Montes Moreno''' (born 12 February 1980 in [[Sensuntepeque]]) is a [[Salvadoran]] former [[Association football|footballer]] last on the team [[Alianza F.C.|Alianza]] in the [[Primera División (El Salvador)|Salvadoran First Division]].
==Club career== On 13 November 2009, Montes was linked with a move to the [[Primera División de México|Primera División]] (First Division) club [[Indios de Ciudad Juárez]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=''La Prensa Grafico''|title=A hablar en México|url=http://www.laprensagrafica.com/deportes/futbol-nacional/72664-a-hablar-en-mexico.html|accessdate=2009-11-13}}</ref> He did not sign with the club, as Indios coach José Treviño stated that reinforcements, including Montes, would not be brought in.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=''El Mexicano''|title=Indios no realizará contrataciones "boom"|url=http://www.oem.com.mx/elmexicano/notas/n1408229.htm|accessdate=2009-11-18}}</ref> On 15 April 2011, Miguel Montes left [[C.D. Águila]] after 2 years in the club, first being capped in the [[Primera División de Fútbol Profesional – Apertura 2009|Apertura 2009]]. He left because the club had not paid him for over a month and a half.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=''El Grafico''|title=Montes deja al Águila |url=http://www.elgrafico.com/destacado-portada/36-destacadas/11568-montes-deja-al-aguila.html|accessdate=2011-04-15|language=es}}</ref> On 14 May 2011, Miguel Montes signed for one year at Isidro Metapán. He told a Salvadoran radio station, "I'm happy because I reached an agreement with the people of Isidro Metapán, they were interested like me and came to the concentration, spoke with me and we reached an agreement."<ref>{{cite web|publisher=''El Salvador FC''|title=Miguel Montes firmó con Isidro Metapán|url=http://www.elsalvadorfc.com/2011-05-14-montes-se-va-para-metapan|accessdate=15 May 2011|language=es|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120730210619/http://www.elsalvadorfc.com/2011-05-14-montes-se-va-para-metapan|archivedate=30 July 2012|df=}}</ref> On May 2012, he signed for [[Alianza F.C.|Alianza]].<ref>http://futbol.univision.com/centroamerica/el-salvador/article/2012-05-11/el-isidro-metapan-confirmo-bajas-y-busca-portero#axzz1uPiMWo7k</ref>
==International career== Montes received call ups to the national team in 1998 and in 2001, but did not get his first cap until 24 May 2004, in a friendly match against [[Haiti national football team|Haiti]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=''RSSSF'' |title=Qualifying Tournament for Gold Cup 2001 - Details |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesg/gold-cam01det.html |accessdate=2008-10-27 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081024005059/http://www.rsssf.com/tablesg/gold-cam01det.html |archivedate=2008-10-24 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|publisher=''RSSSF''|title=International Matches 2004 - North and Central America and Caribbean|url=http://www.rsssf.com/intldetails/2004nca.html|accessdate=2008-10-27}}</ref> Following the Haiti game, Montes was once again neglected by national team coaches, that is until June 2007 when Mexican coach [[Carlos de los Cobos]] called him up to participate in the [[2007 CONCACAF Gold Cup]]. Although he missed out on the opening two game, Montes did play in the team's third and final cup game against the [[United States men's national soccer team|USA]]. Since then, Montes has become a mainstay with the national team.
On 20 March 2010, Montes was given a one-year ban and a fine of $250 by the El Salvador Football Federation on account of not wearing the team's sponsored kit. He wore gloves and socks for a different sponsor on numerous occasions, including the Gold Cup in the U.S in 2009. The federation signed a $600,000 deal with the sponsor in 2008, meaning all players were to wear the same sponsored kit to fulfill the sponsorship deal. [http://www.zimbio.com/Miguel+Montes/articles/dXNCXzG2ir-/El+Salvador+Goalkeeper+Miguel+Montes+Suspended]
After a year of suspension, Montes was called up by then coach [[José Luis Rugamas]] in a friendly international against [[Cuba national football team|Cuba]] on 24 March 2011. He entered as substitute for injured [[Dagoberto Portillo]] in the second half.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=''El Salvador FC'' |title=El Salvador conquered Havana |url=http://www.elsalvadorfc.com/2011-03-24-cuba-vs-elsalvador |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120730211721/http://www.elsalvadorfc.com/2011-03-24-cuba-vs-elsalvador |dead-url=yes |archive-date=2012-07-30 |accessdate=2011-02-24 |language=es }}</ref>
On September 20, 2013, Montes was one of 14 Salvadoran players banned for life due to their involvement with match fixing.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-24184567 |title= El Salvador match-fixing: 14 footballers banned for life |publisher= BBC |accessdate=21 September 2013}}</ref>
